my solution：Observermixin

1. The Abstract LifecycleObserver
The generic S ensures the observer has access to the State, and thus the latest widget.

```
import 'package:flutter/widgets.dart';

/// [V] is the type of the managed value (e.g., AnimationController).
/// [S] is the type of the State that owns this observer.
abstract class LifecycleObserver<V, S extends State> {
  late V value;
  late S _state;

  /// Helper to get the current widget instance.
  dynamic get widget => _state.widget;

  /// Internal initialization called by the Mixin.
  void init(S state) {
    _state = state;
    onInit();
  }

  /// Lifecycle hooks for subclasses to override.
  void onInit() {}
  void onUpdate(covariant StatefulWidget oldWidget) {}
  void onBuild(BuildContext context) {}
  void onDispose() {}
```

2. The Logic Reuse: AnimControllerObserver
This class encapsulates the entire logic of creating, updating, and disposing of an AnimationController.

```
class AnimControllerObserver<S extends State> extends LifecycleObserver<AnimationController, S> {
  final TickerProvider vsync;

  /// A closure to retrieve the latest duration from the widget.
  final Duration Function() durationPicker;

  AnimControllerObserver({
    required this.vsync,
    required this.durationPicker,
  });

  @override
  void onInit() {
    // Initialize the controller with the initial duration.
    value = AnimationController(
      vsync: vsync,
      duration: durationPicker(),
    );
  }

  @override
  void onUpdate(covariant StatefulWidget oldWidget) {
    // Sync logic: Compare current controller duration with the latest picker value.
    final latestDuration = durationPicker();
    if (value.duration != latestDuration) {
      value.duration = latestDuration;
      debugPrint("AnimationController synced to new duration: $latestDuration");
    }
  }

  @override
  void onDispose() {
    value.dispose();
  }
}
```
3. The Orchestrator: ObserverMixin
The mixin manages the lifecycle. It ensures that when the widget is updated, all observers are notified to check for changes.

```
mixin ObserverMixin<T extends StatefulWidget> on State<T> {
  final List<LifecycleObserver<dynamic, State<T>>> _observers = [];

  /// Registers an observer and returns its value.
  V addObserver<V>(LifecycleObserver<V, State<T>> observer) {
    _observers.add(observer);
    observer.init(this);
    return observer.value;
  }

  @override
  void didUpdateWidget(T oldWidget) {
    super.didUpdateWidget(oldWidget);
    // Automatically trigger sync logic in all observers.
    for (var observer in _observers) {
      observer.onUpdate(oldWidget);
    }
  }

  @override
  void dispose() {
    for (var observer in _observers) {
      observer.onDispose();
    }
    _observers.clear();
    super.dispose();
  }

  /// Call this in the build method to enable build-time observation.
  void build(BuildContext context) {
    for (var observer in _observers) {
      observer.onBuild(context);
    }
  }
}
```

4. Clean Usage (Logic Reuse)
The UI developer now only needs to know how to map the widget properties to the observer.
```
class MyLogo extends StatefulWidget {
  final Duration speed;
  const MyLogo({super.key, required this.speed});

  @override
  State<MyLogo> createState() => _MyLogoState();
}

class _MyLogoState extends State<MyLogo> 
    with TickerProviderStateMixin, ObserverMixin<MyLogo> {

  late AnimationController _anim;

  @override
  void initState() {
    super.initState();

    // LOGIC REUSE: Pass a closure '() => widget.speed'. 
    // The observer will call this whenever it needs to sync.
    _anim = addObserver(AnimControllerObserver(
      vsync: this,
      durationPicker: () => widget.speed,
    ));

    _anim.repeat(reverse: true);
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    super.build(context);
    return ScaleTransition(scale: _anim, child: const FlutterLogo());
  }
}
```

Why this achieves Logic Reuse:
 * Zero Boilerplate in State: No dispose(), no manual didUpdateWidget checks.
 * Encapsulated Synchronization: The "how to sync a duration" logic lives inside AnimControllerObserver, not in your UI.

I regularly have multiple animation controllers for different aspects.
This is easy with hooks.
```dart
final enterAnimation = useAnimationController();
final swapAnimation = useAnimationController();
final removeAnimation = useAnimationController();
```

