@lwj1994 
this doesn't strike me as "reusable", the narrow is the use case the more "variations" of this/similar mixin you are going to end up with, (+ tests, maintenance etc)

this point was made by Remi in the very first post

Most non-hook proposals tend to struggle when it comes to passing values that can change at runtime.


Say you make a "fetch HTTP GET and cache it" util (likely with extra work, such as "close the connection if we don't need the response anymore" and co).   
You'll want the util to handle cases where the fetch URI changes.


With hooks you can do something like:

```dart
class BookDetailPage extends StatelessWidget {
  final int bookId;

  @override
  Widget build(context) {
    AsyncSnapshot<Response> response = useFetch('https://my-api/books/$bookId");
  }
}
```

And this would fetch the new book when `bookId` changes (and will abort the previous network request if still pending)

This is difficult to solve with most other proposals, as they tend to be one-off creations due to relying on `late final` or other similar ideas. You'd have to either use funky closure-based APIs or override `didUpdateWidget` to send the updated values, Both of which aren't ideal.

The `key` parameter accepts a `Function()` that is evaluated during [onBuild](cci:1://file:///Volumes/mac-ext-ssd/document/GitHub/state_lifecycle_observer/lib/src/owner_mixin.dart:159:2-162:3). When the returned value changes, the observer automatically:
1. Calls [onDisposeTarget()](cci:1://file:///Volumes/mac-ext-ssd/document/GitHub/state_lifecycle_observer/test/lifecycle_sync_test.dart:20:2-22:3) to clean up (cancel the old request)
2. Calls [buildTarget()](cci:1://file:///Volumes/mac-ext-ssd/document/GitHub/state_lifecycle_observer/test/lifecycle_observer_test.dart:317:2-319:3) to create a new resource

```dart
class FetchObserver extends LifecycleObserver<AsyncSnapshot<Response>> {
  final int Function() bookId;

  FetchObserver(
    super.state, {
    required this.bookId,
  }) : super(key: bookId);  // Key for detecting changes

  @override
  AsyncSnapshot<Response> buildTarget() {
    http.get(Uri.parse('https://my-api/books/${bookId()}')).then((response) {
      target = AsyncSnapshot.withData(ConnectionState.done, response);
      safeSetState(() {});
    });
    return const AsyncSnapshot.waiting();
  }

  @override
  void onDisposeTarget(AsyncSnapshot<Response> target) {
    // Cleanup if needed
  }
}

// Usage - fetch restarts when bookId changes
class _BookDetailState extends State<BookDetailPage> with LifecycleOwnerMixin {
  FetchObserver? fetchObserver;

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    super.build(context);
    fetchObserver ??= FetchObserver(
      this,
      bookId: () => widget.bookId,
    );
    final snapshot = fetchObserver!.target;
    return Text('${snapshot.data}');
  }
}
```

When `widget.bookId` changes:
1. [build()](cci:1://file:///Volumes/mac-ext-ssd/document/GitHub/state_lifecycle_observer/lib/src/owner_mixin.dart:108:2-120:3) calls `super.build(context)` → triggers [onBuild()](cci:1://file:///Volumes/mac-ext-ssd/document/GitHub/state_lifecycle_observer/lib/src/owner_mixin.dart:159:2-162:3)
2. [onBuild()](cci:1://file:///Volumes/mac-ext-ssd/document/GitHub/state_lifecycle_observer/lib/src/owner_mixin.dart:159:2-162:3) detects `key()` value changed
3. [onDisposeTarget()](cci:1://file:///Volumes/mac-ext-ssd/document/GitHub/state_lifecycle_observer/test/lifecycle_sync_test.dart:20:2-22:3) is called → cleanup
4. [buildTarget()](cci:1://file:///Volumes/mac-ext-ssd/document/GitHub/state_lifecycle_observer/test/lifecycle_observer_test.dart:317:2-319:3) is called → starts a new HTTP request with the new bookId
